# Harmony AI App Product Context
@Problems:
- Harmony Link users: AI characters only on desktop/game engines, no mobile access
- Privacy users: Cloud AI collects all data, no private alternative
- Power users: Commercial apps limited customization, closed source
- Offline scenarios: Cloud AI needs constant connection
@Solution:
- Mobile app syncs with Harmony Link backend (self-hosted privacy)
- Open-source codebase (full customization)
- On-device AI via Executorch (offline functionality)
- Flexible backend: Harmony Link (privacy) or Harmony Cloud (convenience)
@Benefits: Complete privacy (self-hosted), anywhere access (mobile), offline capability (local models), full control (open-source), character persistence (cross-device sync).
@UX Goals:
- Simplicity: One-tap cloud setup, clear self-hosted tutorials
- Privacy: Transparent data handling, clear backend mode indication
- Reliability: Stable connections, robust offline, no message loss
- Natural: Realistic timing, character personality, context-aware
@Flow: Setup (choose backend) → Character Selection → Chat (natural conv) → Sync (cross-device) → Offline (graceful fallback).
@Roadmap:
- P1 Foundation: Basic chat, Harmony Link connection, local storage, character selection
- P2 Enhanced: On-device AI, voice (STT/TTS), images, rich profiles
- P3 Integration: Messengers (WhatsApp/Telegram), group chat, multi-character
- P4 Advanced: Custom character creation, memory viz, relationship graphs
@Differentiators: Privacy-first (self-hosted option unique), character persistence (deep memory), open-source (full transparency), ecosystem integration (Harmony Link/games), realistic behavior (advanced timing/personality).
@Metrics: Adoption (MAU, retention), engagement (messages/day, session length), performance (latency, sync reliability), privacy (self-hosted vs cloud split).
@NewCapabilities[SDK+Presets]:
- Extended sampling control: App users benefit from advanced LLM parameters synced from Harmony Link
- Sampling presets: Preset names and custom parameters flow through sync pipeline
- Provider flexibility: Same schema-driven config system as web UI — consistent experience
- Fine-tuned responses: typical_p, tfs, dry_* params enable better response quality control
- Future-proof: openai-go v3 SDK ensures compatibility with latest OpenAI API features
@NewCapabilities[Phase09]:
- More provider options: New LLM API parameters exposed in management UI flow to app
- Better config control: Key-value list editing for advanced parameters
- Consistent config: Same provider field schemas as Harmony Link web frontend
- Note: Lifecycle settings (autonomy config) added to web UI but app handles autonomy locally
@NewCapabilities[ProviderExpansion]:
- 15 provider types supported (up from 9): Added Google (Gemini), xAI (Grok), Anthropic (Claude)
- Model field unification: Simplified provider configs with single `model` column
- Movement module: Google/xAI/Anthropic provider options for character movement AI
- Schema-driven UI: No module-specific schemas — one schema per provider, clean and consistent
- Dead code eliminated: Module-specific field schemas merged, shared isProviderConfigInUse helper
